text.text:
Get Well Soon...😟❣️
We visited Notre dame Cathedral in December 2019.. Due to some tragic fire, it's closed until further notice. So entry was not possible. But still we can have a look from distance. It's worth walking around even after fire. The architecture is magnificent. Initially we couldn't recognise what happened actually to the cathedral. But as we walked towards it, the extent of damages were obvious at the sides and back. Hopefully the recovery process will be over and everyone can have an overwhelming and mind-blowing visit inside the cathedral soon. ☺️

NB: beware of pickpockets around the attractions as well as in Metro. 😣

text.text: WC = water closet = bathroom = rest room = toilet. If you are looking at the front of Notre Dame, it’s around to the right. There’s a small blue sign on a post and go down the stairs and then down the hallway.  It costs $2 because the bathroom is attended by a person who keeps it stocked and clean. You can pay cash or card at the kiosk. For some cards, the attendant will need to use a smaller card reader instead of the kiosk.

text.text: I was in the middle of Paris enjoying fabulous views of the Eiffel Tower when I had to pee badly due to the cafe au lait I had earlier that morning.  After waiting on a long line of tourists who also had to go, my time to pee had come.  What a relief!  I highly recommend le toilette for all of your urinary needs.  It was a real lifesaver.  Free public toilets throughout the city.... why can't the rest of the world be like Paris?!

text.text:
I've been to Paris long ago, but one of the highlights is the chance of civilized toilets by pointwc. I can't tell how grateful I was for this service - never ever had a chance to use a public toilet like the one at home. then it was just 4 locations. price in 2015 was exactly the same and it was worth every cent as you have to pay for human labor - and not on a slave level my dear cheap fellow human beings...
buy a card, then you get it for 1€/occasion. please don't tell me it's worth to pay 5€ for a coffee and not 1 for the outcome... ;-)

i wish they'd open a business everywhere on this Planet.

no cash is a bit of surprise, but not in the developed world, Sweden plans to stop cash in 2025, so wake up people.
